  SOLID PRINCIPLES
  ------------------
  SOLID PRINCIPLES

  These principles help us write code that is:

  1) Clean

  2) Flexible

  3) Easy to understand

  4) Easy to test

  5) Easy to maintain

==================================================================================
  S stands for Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
  "One class ----> One Job"
  One class need to have only one responsiblity.

  Why ?
  Ans:- Because each operation has a different reason to change.
  Splitting improves maintainability, readabiltiy, testing and reduces
  side effects.

  Ans:- Because every responsibility has a different reason to change.
  If one class handles multiple responsibilities, it will break for multiple reasons.


  Let us take an example we have UserService Class have multiple jobs
   1) Save User
   2) sendEmail
   3) generateReport

   Now this class changes if:
   DB changes ->(Sql to MongoDB)
   Email logic changes
   Report format changes


   --------------------- Bad Example --------------------
   class UserService{
        public void saveUser(){

        }
        public void sendEmail(){

        }
        public void generateReport(){

        }
   }

 ---------------- Good Example ------------------

   class UserRepo{
        public void save(){

        }
   }

   class EmailService{
        public void sendEmail(){

        }
   }

   class ReportRepo{
        public void generateReport(){

        }
   }


=================================================================================*

   O stands for Open/Closed Principle (ocp)
   "Open for extension closed for modification"


   Adding new Behaviour without rewriting the existing code.

  We should not make CameraService Class
  we make a CameraService interface we implement with brand classes

Let take a scenario
We support multiple camera brands:
* Hikvision
* Dahua
* Cp Plus

If we created a class

class CameraService {
   void connect(String brand){
	   if(brand.equals("Hikvision")){

	   }
	   else if(brand.equals("Cp Plus")){

	   }
	   else if(brand.equals("Dahua")){

	   }
   }
}

for every new brand, we need to modify the class. That's Fragile.

Proper Design
We Create a interface for Cameras and we implement with specific brand classes

interface CameraBrand{
	void connect();
}

class HikivisionCamera implements CameraBrand {

}
class CpplusCamera implements CameraBrand {

}
class DahuaCamera implements CameraBrand{

}

No modification required.
Only extension.
================================================================================
   L stands for Liskov Substitution Principle(LSP)
   "Child classes must behave like parent classes."

   Think we created a class Camera and in that we have two methods hdd recording and non-hdd recording

   class Camera{
        public void record(){
        }
        public void hddRecord(){
        }
   }

   we have a hdd camera and non-hdd camera
   class HDDCamera extends Camera{

   }
   class NonHDDCamera extends Camera{
   }


   If we create instance for both non hdd camera cannot implement hdd record
   It fails there so here comes the LSP Rule

   The flaw
   You forced every camera to have hddRecord().
   But a NonHDDCamera does not support HDD recording.

   Camera cam = new NonHDDCamera();
   cam.hddRecord();
	Now you have only two bad choices:
	Throw an exception ❌
	Leave the method empty ❌
	Both mean the child class cannot behave like the parent, which violates LSP.
	Your reasoning is right, but the explanation should clearly show the failure.

	we need to design correct----
	class Camera {
	    public void record() {
	        System.out.println("Recording video");
	    }
	}

	class HDDCamera extends Camera {
        public void hddRecord() {
            System.out.println("Recording to HDD");
        }
    }
    class NonHDDCamera extends Camera {

    }

    Camera cam1 = new HDDCamera();
    cam1.record();

    Camera cam2 = new NonHDDCamera();
    cam2.record();

    HDDCamera hddCam = new HDDCamera();
    hddCam.hddRecord();

	now whether the camera is hdd or not depends on that we can use the class and not breaks lsp rule.

	Suppose we design a Camera class with methods record() and hddRecord().
    But not all cameras support HDD recording.
    If a NonHDDCamera extends Camera, it cannot implement hddRecord().
    This means the subclass cannot behave like the parent class, which violates the Liskov Substitution Principle.

    To fix this, we should keep the base Camera class minimal and move hddRecord() only to the HDDCamera class.

================================================================================
   I Stands for Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
   "Don't force classes to implement things they don't use."

   Suppose we have CameraService interface in that we perform some operations
   1) Camera with mic
   2) Camera with nightvision
   3) Camera can rotate

   we should not implement all this functionality in one interface because
   some cameras can rotate|| availble mic || nightvision or not
   If created by we don't use them in that but still we need to implement

   so make them separate interfaces so according to that we can implement

---------- BAD Example -----------
   interface Camera{
        void stream();
        void rotate();
        void enableNightvision();
        void communicate();
   }
-----------Good example -------------

	interface Streamble{
	    void Stream();
	}
	interface Rotatable{
		void rotate();
	}
	interface NightVisionCapable{
		void enableNightVision();
	}
	interface microphone{
		void communicate();
	}


so using this interface according we can implement with our specific cameras

================================================================================
## D — Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)

**Definition**

The **Dependency Inversion Principle** states:

* **High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules.**
* **Both should depend on abstractions.**

Also:

* **Abstractions should not depend on details.**
* **Details should depend on abstractions.**

---

## Key Idea

* **High-level module** → Business logic / policy
* **Low-level module** → Implementation / technical details

Examples of low-level modules:

* Database
* File storage
* Email sender
* SMS gateway
* Logger
* Payment gateway

Business logic should **not directly depend on these implementations**.

---

# ❌ Example (Violation of DIP)

```java
class CameraController {

    AwsStorage storage = new AwsStorage();

    void record(Video video) {
        storage.save(video);
    }
}
```

### What is happening here?

* `CameraController` → **High-level module** (surveillance business logic)
* `AwsStorage` → **Low-level module** (cloud storage implementation)

### Problem

`CameraController` is **directly dependent on AwsStorage**.

If the storage changes to:

* Azure Storage
* Local HDD storage
* FTP server
* NVR storage

Then **CameraController must be modified**.

This creates **tight coupling**, which violates the Dependency Inversion Principle.

---

# ✅ Correct Design (Following DIP)

First create an **abstraction**.

```java
interface Storage {
    void save(Video video);
}
```

Then implement the abstraction.

```java
class AwsStorage implements Storage {
    public void save(Video video) {
        System.out.println("Saving video to AWS");
    }
}

class AzureStorage implements Storage {
    public void save(Video video) {
        System.out.println("Saving video to Azure");
    }
}
```

Now inject the dependency.

```java
class CameraController {

    private Storage storage;

    CameraController(Storage storage) {
        this.storage = storage;
    }

    void record(Video video) {
        storage.save(video);
    }
}
```

### Usage

```java
CameraController controller1 = new CameraController(new AwsStorage());
CameraController controller2 = new CameraController(new AzureStorage());
```

Now the controller depends on **Storage abstraction**, not a specific implementation.

---

# Dependency Flow

```
CameraController  →  Storage
AwsStorage        →  Storage
AzureStorage      →  Storage
```

All modules depend on the **abstraction**.

---

# Benefits of Following DIP

If DIP is **not followed**:

* Code becomes tightly coupled
* Switching technologies becomes difficult
* Testing becomes harder
* Maintenance cost increases

If DIP **is followed**:

* Implementations can be swapped easily
* Code becomes flexible
* Unit testing becomes easier
* System becomes easier to maintain

---

# Simple Interview Explanation

> Dependency Inversion Principle states that high-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.
>
> For example, in a surveillance system a `CameraController` should not directly depend on `AwsStorage`. Instead it should depend on a `Storage` interface. Different implementations like `AwsStorage` or `AzureStorage` implement this interface.
>
> This allows us to change the storage system without modifying the business logic.
